06905nam a22010335i 9780812205169DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20112012pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979592105  a97808122051697 a10.9783/97808122051692doi  a(DE-B1597)449486  a(OCoLC)794700695  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHQ792.U5bR374 2012eb 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a305.2309182/10904522300aReinventing Childhood After World War II /ced. by Michael Grossberg, Paula S. Fass. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. The Child-Centered Family? New Rules in Postwar America -- t2. Liberation and Caretaking: Fighting over Children’s Rights in Postwar America -- t3. The Changing Face of Children’s Culture -- t4. Ten Is the New Fourteen: Age Compression and “Real” Childhood -- t5. Whose Child? Parenting and Custody in the Postwar Period -- t6. Children, the State, and the American Dream -- t7. Children and the Swedish Welfare State: From Different to Similar -- tNotes -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the Western world, the modern view of childhood as a space protected from broader adult society first became a dominant social vision during the nineteenth century. Many of the West's sharpest portrayals of children in literature and the arts emerged at that time in both Europe and the United States and continue to organize our perceptions and sensibilities to this day. But that childhood is now being recreated.Many social and political developments since the end of the World War II have fundamentally altered the lives children lead and are now beginning to transform conceptions of childhood. Reinventing Childhood After World War II brings together seven prominent historians of modern childhood to identify precisely what has changed in children's lives and why. Topics range from youth culture to children's rights; from changing definitions of age to nontraditional families; from parenting styles to how American experiences compare with those of the rest of the Western world. Taken together, the essays argue that children's experiences have changed in such dramatic and important ways since 1945 that parents, other adults, and girls and boys themselves have had to reinvent almost every aspect of childhood.Reinventing Childhood After World War II presents a striking interpretation of the nature and status of childhood that will be essential to students and scholars of childhood, as well as policy makers, educators, parents, and all those concerned with the lives of children in the world today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAdolescencezSwedenxHistoryx20th century. 0aAdolescencezSwedenxHistoryx21st century. 0aAdolescencezSwedenxHistoryy20th century. 0aAdolescencezSwedenxHistoryy21st century. 0aAdolescencezUnited StatesxHistoryx20th century. 0aAdolescencezUnited StatesxHistoryx21st century. 0aAdolescencezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aAdolescencezUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aChildrenxSocial conditions. 0aChildrenzSwedenxSocial conditionsxHistoryx20th century. 0aChildrenzSwedenxSocial conditionsxHistoryx21st century. 0aChildrenzSwedenxSocial conditionsxHistoryy20th century. 0aChildrenzSwedenxSocial conditionsxHistoryy21st century. 0aChildrenzUnited StatesxSocial conditionsxHistoryx20th century. 0aChildrenzUnited StatesxSocial conditionsxHistoryx21st century. 0aChildrenzUnited StatesxSocial conditionsxHistoryy20th century. 0aChildrenzUnited Stat